description.plain:
​mewithoutYou is a band comprised of brothers Aaron and Michael Weiss, Brandon Beaver and Rickie Mazzotta. They play a unique blend of post-hardcore, emo, and spoken word music with lyrics (written by Aaron Weiss) that draw inspiration from Christianity, Islam, ancient fables, and myriad other items of religious and cultural folklore.

The Weiss brothers were raised by a Jewish father and Episcopal mother who both converted to Sufi Islam. This influence permeates throughout the lyrics in their collection, and there is an overarching message of finding G-d, or at least some semblance of truth in existence. Michael Weiss provides a caveat to that, however:

We don’t really try to claim that we are the ambassadors of that truth ourselves, or that the Bible, or the Koran, or Bawa Muhaiyaddeen are. These truths just exist, and everybody sort of has a way to know them, to experience them, to live them… If you really want to just try to follow a path to God, I don’t believe you need anything beyond [your beliefs], but it’s just the idea that you’re fixed on the only way and that everybody else is just completely misguided… that is a sort of obtuse attitude that can hurt your own spirit.

​In 2018, mewithoutYou released their seventh album [Untitled], which was preceded with the [untitled] e.p. through Run For Cover Records.

In 2019, mewithoutYou announced their retirement, citing that 2020 would be their last year as an active band.

Current members:
Aaron Weiss – lead vocals, acoustic guitar, accordion, trumpet, keyboards, percussion
Michael Weiss – guitar, keyboards, vocals
Rickie Mazzotta – drums
Greg Jehanian – bass guitar, vocals
Brandon Beaver – guitar, vocals

Past members:
Dominic Angelella -bass guitar, vocals
Christopher Kleinberg – guitar
Daniel Pishock – bass guitar, vocals, keyboards
Ray Taddeo – guitar

songs.title: Rainbow Signs

description.plain:
A melodic, lyrical and thematic continuation of both “Pale Horses” and “Dorothy,” “Rainbow Signs” pairs references to the Apocalypse, as told by the Book of Revelations, with Aaron Weiss‘ struggle to cope with his father’s death.

Weiss has indicated that the song was originally intended to conclude with the instrumental breakdown, but Weiss ultimately decided to “bring it back to a personal place where I can speak with some authority because this is my own experience,” concluding with the dream-like anecdote about his father.

songs.title: Mexican War Streets

description.plain:
Aaron seems to be exploring many Modernist poets on the album as a whole. The constant referral to bridges in this song is likely influenced by Hart Crane, and his obsession with Bridges as religious symbols for modern society. Especially at the end of this song, when he starts in with very poetic descriptions of the bridge itself as a symbol for bridging gaps between two people or beings. In this case, I believe he is alluding to the gap between human consciousness, as he uses James Joyce to illustrate the gap between our own thoughts. He may also be alluding to the “gap” between man and god, and is also very likely considering the ocean between him and his wife.

Throughout the album, Aaron alludes to an “ocean” that is separating people. In this song he quotes from “White Nights,” which is about a man who thought he would be a hermit the rest of his life. He then meets a girl, who ultimately doesn’t love him back. The man is left pondering what it will mean to be alone forever, even though he remains optimistic.

This is what Aaron thought was destined for his life, but “nature had another plan.”

Read Hart Crane’s “The Bridge” for more context. If Aaron is not referencing this directly, he is certainly following the “metanarrative” tropes of Modernist literature throughout the album, and references Joyce in this song.

I might call this a good example or “remodernist” art.

songs.title: Messes of Men

description.plain:
As with many other tracks on this album, these lyrics are heavily influenced by Sufi poetry. It could be argued that this track’s narrative is derived from the poem “Only Breath” by Rumi.

“Not Christian or Jew or Muslim, not Hindu, Buddhist, Sufi, or zen. Not any religion or cultural system. I am not from the East or the West, not out of the ocean or up from the ground, not natural or ethereal, not composed of elements at all. I do not exist, am not an entity in this world or in the next, did not descend from Adam and Eve or any origin story. My place is placeless, a trace of the traceless. Neither body or soul. I belong to the beloved, have seen the two worlds as one and that one call to and know, first, last, outer, inner, only that breath breathing human being.”

The vocal track for this song was done outside in the rain, according to an Instagram post by producer Brad Wood. The rain is audible on the final product and lends an authentic air to the track which focuses on nautical themes and settings.

songs.title: January 1979

description.plain:
“January 1979” is a song themed around Aaron Weiss’s failure as a human in life. He and former bassist, Daniel Pishock, were both born in January 1979. The “crash” Aaron explains refers to his birth. Aaron wrote this song discussing his frustration surrounding his “overfed, unconcerned, and comfortably numb” existence. Realizing his failure, he sings of becoming a servant of all, a reference to Matthew 23:11. Becoming the lowest would imply that there would no longer be any possibility of failing more. While he remarks that his eyes have become useless, the song ends with hope of a cure. His concept about grasshoppers may reference to Numbers 13:33, or Isaiah 40:22. The line “My ear pressed against the past / like a glass on the wall of a house in a photograph” closely resembles a line in Richard Brautigan’s novel So the Wind Won’t Blow It All Away.

description.plain:
The second track on MeWithoutYou’s album “It’s All Crazy! It’s All False! It’s All a Dream! It’s Alright”, “The Fox, the Crow and the Cookie” is a retelling/ re-imagining of Aesop’s Fable “The Fox and the Crow,” a short tale that demonstrates the pitfalls of the ego.

In the original fable, the fox is able to steal food from the crow by tricking him to drop it from his beak by singing, and the moral, as stated by the fox, is “not to trust flatterers,” or fall victim to your own vanity.

This is mirrored in MeWithoutYou’s version as the crow’s self-indulgent verse causes him to lose out on the shortbread cookie and German chocolate tart.

While there is some artistic license taken, the song stays very true to its source material.



The song is, along with the rest of the album, inspired by the teachings of Sufi mystic Bawa Muhaiyaddeen rather than Aesop. In his collection My Love You My Children: 101 Stories for Children, he has a story known as “The Fox, the Crow, and the Cookie”, which is probably where the inspiration for the song came from.

Of course, Bawa’s own fable was most likely inspired by Aesop’s, hence the common misconception.

Through mostly vacant streets
A baker from the outskirts of his town
Earned his living peddling sweets

Looking down was the hungry crow:
"When the time is right, I'll strike
And condescend to the earth below
And take whichever treat I'd like"
The moment the baker turned around

description.plain:
About the lyrical style of this album:

“This time around with writing I tried to avoid having a single theme that ran across the entire album, simply because I didn’t want to repeat the last approach. I also didn’t want it to be a total hodgepodge of non-related content, which is what some of our earlier albums were. I tried to split the difference, where I picked a few different themes and separated them. I wrote a bunch of content under each theme and then mixed and matched content from each of those themes to make different songs. There’s probably 5-10 different themes on the album, several of which show up in each song.”

description.plain:
This song is in a sense ambiguous.  One reading is that the only way to truly understand God is to leave earthly life behind and commune with Him directly.

On another level, the fire is merely a part of the physical world that the beetles do not understand, though they mistakenly believe it to be God.  However in this reading it is a false idol, and the Beetle King’s attempt to use the fire as a means of understanding God are ultimately misguided and self-destructive.

songs.title: Dorothy

description.plain:
“Dorothy” is the 6th track on Pale Horses and flows seamlessly in from the track before, “Red Cow”.

In it, Weiss recalls a dream of college and reminisces on his recently-deceased father, and seems to relate that to the cry of “Eloi, Eloi, lama sabachthani” – which references the cry of Christ: Eli, Eli, lama sabachthani (translates to “My God, My God, why have you forsaken me?”).

Aaron here uses “Eloi”, a closer word to his father’s name, “Elliot”.

The relation is completed in the last line, “Elliot, Eloi, Eloi”.

songs.title: Birnam Wood

description.plain: Aaron expresses paranoia in this song about whether God approves of him, or whether God has “grown weary of his saints?” and has abandoned him. Aaron has said that he experienced a nervous breakdown, as referred to in this song. The song also discusses a poisoned Russian dissident, who many believe was killed at the behest of the Russian government. Would God do the same to an errant believer? Additionally, the song mentions Macbeth multiple times, and that play often reflects on paranoia. At the end of the song, the singer begs God to untie him from this anxiety or mental illness, which hangs as a knife above his head.

songs.title: February, 1878

description.plain:
Setting the stage for the rest of the album, February 1878 details the wrecking of a circus train, and the circus animals subsequent escape. According to lead singer Aaron Weiss, the song was inspired by a story William James included in chapter 4 of his monumental work “The Principles of Psychology”.

The title and lyrical themes of February 1878 reference “January 1979” from mewithoutYou’s second album, Catch for Us the Foxes, making it yet another of of the band’s “sequel songs”.

songs.title: Torches Together

description.plain:
“Torches Together” was written in light of Aaron Weiss’s experience at The Simple Way and Brouderhoff, two communities that take the idea of church as seriously as the early church. While there Aaron wrote this song. “The song off our new record, ‘Torches Together,’ talks about community and coming together and loving each other.”[7] He also references his previous suicidal tendencies: “anyway, aren’t you unbearably sad?” and looks into the Simple Way philosophy of living simply and with no plans: “so never mind of plan making, we’ll start living.” He also uses common biblical concepts of the church like a building (1 Peter 2:4-5), being the light of the world (Matthew 5:14), and quotes Proverbs 26:14 with “turning like a door on its hinges” and references Luke 11:33 when He says “Why burn…under a bowl…”. The song ends with a reference to Matthew 11:16-17.

songs.title: Four Word Letter (Pt. 2)

description.plain:
“Four Word Letter (Pt.2)” is an interesting song born out of the difference in the faith of Aaron and his family. While there seems to be a bit of meaninglessness, “..aimlessly drifting around.” there is a yearning for purpose even in doubt: “Oh, doubters, let’s go down, down to the river to pray..” borrowing from Down in the River to Pray, a traditional hymn. There is a bit of discussion about seeking out God coming from his family, to which he responds appropriately to each excuse. However, Aaron admits that he does not desire his beliefs or those of his family, but rather to have the “God of peace.” By using imagery of a song and its artist comparing them to God and his creation, he shows the absurdity of complaining, even if its “clever” or philosophical. The real “hunger” is not satisfied with a set of beliefs, whether Christian or Islamic. Fans often express belief that the four word letter is “Jesus I love you” or “I love you goodbye”

It is a continuation and/or sequel to the track “Four Word Letter” from the EP I Never Said That I Was Brave.

songs.title: Tie Me Up! Untie Me!

description.plain:
“Tie Me Up! Untie Me!” shows themes of suicide and the mysterious salvation of the Lord.[citation needed] Weiss begins with a search for someone, probably God, on the “tops of the trees”, where a glorious God should be found, but with no success. He rather finds that Jesus is “buried” and mostly left unnoticed. Despite Weiss’s inability to find God, God grabbed him, like a sickness. Then his “sweetheart moved away,” possibly referring to his previous relationship with sin or the world (with further references to this girl in the chorus). However this provided more tension as Weiss goes on to speak of his distance from God, and his fickleness is obeying God or obey his flesh (“Tie me up! Untie me!). Suicide seems to be a major distraction. Again he describes the search for God, and his surprise in finding God in a "dull shell.” The song ends with witness of victory over seemingly unsurmountable tendencies towards suicide. He takes from Rumi using the line: “Love moves away. The light changes. I need more grace than I thought.[3]”

songs.title: [dormouse sighs]

description.plain:
I believe this song is an internal monologue, expounding the state of mind of Aaron Weiss prior to his highway-side revelation in West Virginia, which is frequently reference in both [Untitled] and the [untitled] e.p.

Most, if not all, of the named speakers in this song, can be understood as various aspects of Aaron’s mind, much like the proverbial angels and demons perched on ones shoulder.  Together they seem to be struggling with a loss of purpose and or faith.  This seems to related to the question of the surety of salvation, a theme which is addressed previously in 9:27, 7/29.  The possibility of Christ’s return (“Before the day is done, My prince is gonna come,”) and of death (Josephine Foster and Nikolai Volkoff) put these concerns into a stark and difficult contrast.

These concerns and the depression and withdrawal associated with them seem to be answered in the revelations on the West Virginia highway-side, although Aaron chooses not to divulge what this revalation is, but only to reaffirm the “wonder-working power” of G-d.

Barren rocks and sand, Our wooden sculpture hands

As the audience cheered for us. We burned like fevers under carriage hats
Hid behind Venetian masks in our human costumes

Wrapped border drab around already broken ironstone."

"But I've seen these cliffs before, St. Agnes brought her palm branch
To the hospital, looked upward lest the charm had fled from my brother's breathing bed

Look how soon my hands won't move - but if you'll improve, we'll all improve
Look how soon my arms won't move!
Sixty feet and my feet won't move, but if you'll improve, we'll all improve

songs.title: My Exit, Unfair

description.plain:
“My Exit, Unfair” is a song Aaron wrote about his mother. He refers to the Biblical account of Jonah and his foolishness is fleeing from God’s plans for him. The realization is that “a hard rain is going to fall.” The emptiness and failures of men are temporary while deep inside us the eternal is written, an allusion to Ecclesiastes 3:11. The end of the song is a Islamic prayer that Aaron prayed as a child, that he learned from his mother [9] translated “Oh Most Patient, Glory be to Thee, I seek refuge in you from Satan the accursed. Praise be to God. In the name of God, Most Gracious, Most Compassionate, Most Merciful.”[10]

songs.title: Paper-Hanger

description.plain:
“Paper Hanger” is about dying to find life in Christ. Aaron lightly borrows from the story of Jesus turning water into wine at a banquet as told in John 2. “She was like wine turned to water then turned back to wine.” This line might refer to the perfect creation of God turning away from God and then turned back to God again. The surrender to God offered in the lyrics “My life is no longer mine” leads him to fit into the function of community that provides wholeness. Men, when they “stop [their] leaving” and show unselfish commitment, that therein lies the betterment of men. Lyrics quote the Gospel of Thomas: “If they ask you, ‘What is the sign of your father within you?’ say to them, ‘It is movement and repose.’” Stevan Davies explains: “The seven days of Genesis begin with the Spirit moving upon the waters, continue through six days of the movement of creation, and conclude with a day of repose.” [8]

songs.title: August 6th

description.plain:
This song seems to reference the bombing of Hiroshima on August 6th, 1945. The first half creates an image of a world of innocence challenged by the ability of war and even modern life to eradicate such innocence. The second verse pivots to the internal thoughts of one of the affected – left choking for air, screaming in a neighborhood-turned-graveyard. He observes destruction of both human life and of the supposed luxuries of human life.

There is also the possibility that the song is also protest of US foreign policy. The first half is definitely painting a more peaceful place at home, but the US has not had a war on its own turf in forever. This leads a lot of people to have an “innocence of war” while the country is simultaneously causing a lot of destruction on the other side of the world, indicated by the second half of the song.  Aaron has actually been arrested before protesting foreign policy at the pentagon, indicated in the song Timothy Hay.

“Me and Sister Margaret on the Pentagon lawn
With our wrists in a plastic tie.”"

description.plain:
Nice and Blue is the third track from [A→B] Life, mewithoutYou’s debut album.

The song is reprised in their 2006 album Brother, Sister.

songs.title: Seven Sisters

description.plain:
“Seven Sisters” is written considering creation and the place of humans in it. The Creator made things soft and easy. However, men’s clever philosophy is simply neat arrangements and men are left try to discover “where to sleep.” He paraphrases a quote from “Icon of Light”, a prayer written by Symeon the New Theologian. “Come, Light that knows no evening come, alone to the alone.”[5]. Aaron also uses the ideas of Rumi: “A thousand half-loves must be forsaken to take one whole heart home”,[6] and then again in the next line: “You dance inside my chest, where no one sees you, but sometimes I do..”[7]. These two prayers form a plea to the Creator to give men a madness that is whole, and to offer a resting place. The chorus refers to the cleansing and salvation found in God. The expectation continues that men are “expected to believe that any of this is real. The lines "covered like carpets with graceful, meaningless ornamental designs” comes from the novel The Journey To The East by Hermann Hesse."

songs.title: Cardiff Giant

description.plain:
[This] song is a dialogue between the tiger and the peacock, both of whom stayed in captivity for different reasons. The tiger was very deliberate in remaining because of his sense of internal freedom regardless of external circumstances, but the peacock just feels kind of stuck. And the first time it’s the peacock saying “I often wonder if I’ve already died,” meaning a sense of having squandered her freedom—she missed the opportunity to escape and she’s stuck in this life that has no purpose or growth. And then the tiger responds in the second chorus saying the same thing, but it means almost the exact opposite—the tiger is wondering if the ego has been annihilated, if the self has been totally surrendered, and the tiger has been taken to some new, higher level of consciousness or reality. So it’s taking the same exact sentence and flipping it on its head.

– Aaron Weiss in a “Rank Your Records” interview with Vice

songs.title: Carousels

description.plain:
“Carousels” is a song about the foolishness of the world and the true need for God. Aaron wrote this song after riding into town one day. He was struck by the billboards and consumerism found in the American culture. This realization leads him to lay prostrate before God. As the Israelites once wandered in the desserts of Sinai, so Weiss admits that he would wander without God. He also expresses the meaninglessness and evil of existence apart from God’s existence. He quotes Jack Kerouac’s book The Dharma Bums when he sings: “Like a horn blown by some sad angel.” There is also a plea for Jesus to come back, referring to his expected return. In the background of the first verse, “Jesus, remember me when you come into your kingdom,” is heard – the words of the criminal crucified beside Jesus who repented. In the second verse “we bow in unity when we come into your kingdom” is heard instead.

songs.title: Yellow Spider

description.plain:
Yellow Spider is the first installment of Brother, Sister’s “spider trilogy”.

Originally one song, but separated into the three tracks we know them as today for Brother, Sister, the spider songs are still related musically and thematically. The lyrics are inspired by an observation from the life of the writer, Aaron Weiss:

It was written as one song based on seeing a brown spider and it was on a brown leaf. I just thought of the way that animals get by and the food is provided for them. Then the leaves fall off of the trees and then they come back the next year, and how everything works real well. So I write all the lyrics keeping that in mind…
- interview for Lambgoat

Together, the trilogy serves to further illustrate a concept common to much of the album’s lyrics: spiritual death to one’s “self”/ego in order to better serve and follow God (a recurring message found in the New Testament). The leaf can serve as a symbol of the singer’s ego, progressively wilting from yellow to orange to brown and ultimately dying/decaying/disappearing along with the singer’s “self” at the end of the series, Brownish Spider (“no more spider, no more leaf, no more me, no more belief”).

The three tracks have similar structure and melody, but each feature unique instrumentation that is heard in other songs throughout Brother, Sister, serving to further tie the album together.

See also:
- Yellow Spider
- Orange Spider
- Brownish Spider

description.plain:
“I Never Said That I Was Brave” is the ninth song from mewithoutYou’s debut album, [A→B] Life.

It was also the first track on the EP with the same name.

The title seems to be taken from a Leonard Cohen line about suicide from “So Long Marianne”:

For now I need your hidden love
I’m cold as a new razor blade
You left when I told you I was curious
I never said that I was brave

An acoustic version of this song was included in the album as a hidden track after “The Cure for Pain”.

Weiss is regretting separating with his love, and now is wishing she’d invite him in and take him back. This is a change of direction from the confidence he expressed in his decision to separate from her in the first half of the album.

songs.title: Leaf

description.plain:
“Leaf” likely is a song born out of Aaron’s sudden change from caring about his clothing and dance style to his disgust with showiness and fame. In an interview[4] by Relevant Magazine he comments about clothes “I feel embarrassed buying food when it’s being thrown away everywhere I look! And dressing up in new clothes every day, trying to look attractive or desirable and stay clean and respectable—it’s a lot of effort, and I don’t have it in me anymore. When I see people with their hair done and make up and stylish clothes, it looks silly to me now, like a costume.” He goes on in the song to say that logical talk, or dancing or even singing is stupid and doesn’t allow God inside of him to speak at all. He rather desires purity of heart in his “call to love my brother.” The chorus is a reference to Søren Kierkegaard’s work “Purity of Heart is to Will One Thing”.

songs.title: Cleo’s Ferry Cemetery

description.plain:
“Cleo’s Ferry Cemetery” is mewithoutYou’s cover/rewritten version of Say Anything’s “Cemetery” along with lyrics borrowed from “Baby Girl, I’m a Blur.” This song, along with Say Anything’s “Torches Apart” will be available on their tour-only 7" split.



“Cleo’s Ferry Cemetery” premiered through the FADER website along with Say Anything’s “Torches Apart.” MewithoutYou vocalist Aaron Weiss shared with the FADER:

The original version of “Cemetery” embodies what I love about Say Anything: vividly corporal, emotionally confrontational, self-deprecating, brutally honest, cynical/dark while weirdly hopeful, etc. He sings way better than I can, so why bother covering his song outright? Better to do something our own, even if it’s inferior, at least it’s not only inferior. Cobbling together lines of Max’s, lines of mine, a Morrissey lyric, it’s harder to know who gets credit if it turns out well, who’s to blame if it fails, probably accounting for the somewhat-less-anxiety-ridden-than-usual song production process. All this plus we can recommend a visit to Cleo’s Ferry Museum in Melba, Idaho—a partial-cure place, I think, for what ails ‘people’ like me and Max.

The original version of “Cemetery” embodies what I love about Say Anything: vividly corporal, emotionally confrontational, self-deprecating, brutally honest, cynical/dark while weirdly hopeful, etc. He sings way better than I can, so why bother covering his song outright? Better to do something our own, even if it’s inferior, at least it’s not only inferior. Cobbling together lines of Max’s, lines of mine, a Morrissey lyric, it’s harder to know who gets credit if it turns out well, who’s to blame if it fails, probably accounting for the somewhat-less-anxiety-ridden-than-usual song production process. All this plus we can recommend a visit to Cleo’s Ferry Museum in Melba, Idaho—a partial-cure place, I think, for what ails ‘people’ like me and Max.

songs.title: Aubergine

description.plain:
This song tells the story of a vegetable in a withering garden. The speaker is caught up in their own [solipsism] (https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/solipsism) until the image of a dying friend, the spinach, causes them to reconsider the significance of others.

The story begins with the speaker struggling to answer the question posed at the end. This theme of the cyclical nature of life is central to the album as stated directly in [All Circles] (https://genius.com/Mewithoutyou-all-circles-lyrics).

description.plain:
Break on Through (to the Other Side) is a song by the Doors. Taking from Aaron’s habit of writing sequel songs, he has instead this time written a sequel to another band’s song (which he’s already expressed interest in doing so for Belle & Sebatian’s song The State I Am In on New Wine, New Skins).

Break on Through to the Other Side is also in reference to a conversation Aaron had on the podcast The Wandering Wolf with Yoni Wolf. On the podcast, Yoni describes his experience with trying the drug DMT for the first time. Yoni states that the drug is a made up of a chemical that our bodies release when we die. He describes his experience of taking DMT and how it made him lose his sense of self and how he “broke through to the other side.”

Aaron is summarizing the album that he hopes that after all his “mental collapses,” his questions of faith and religion in god, and whatever other internal and external struggles he faces, one day he’ll find his true self that he is finally at peace with.

songs.title: Orange Spider

description.plain:
Orange Spider is the second song of Brother, Sister’s “spider trilogy”.

Originally one song, but separated into the three tracks we know them as today for Brother, Sister, the spider songs are still related musically and thematically. The lyrics are inspired by an observation from the life of the writer, Aaron Weiss:

It was written as one song based on seeing a brown spider and it was on a brown leaf. I just thought of the way that animals get by and the food is provided for them. Then the leaves fall off of the trees and then they come back the next year, and how everything works real well. So I write all the lyrics keeping that in mind…
- interview for Lambgoat

Together, the trilogy serves to further illustrate a concept common to much of the album’s lyrics: spiritual death to one’s “self”/ego in order to better serve and follow God (a recurring message found in the New Testament). The leaf can serve as a symbol of the singer’s ego, progressively wilting from yellow to orange to brown and ultimately dying/decaying/disappearing along with the singer’s “self” at the end of the series, Brownish Spider (“no more spider, no more leaf, no more me, no more belief”).

The three tracks have similar structure and melody, but each feature unique instrumentation that is heard in other songs throughout Brother/Sister, serving to further tie the album together.

See also:
- Yellow Spider
- Orange Spider
- Brownish Spider
